## Overview

The goal of this project is to implement an IRC server compatible with standard IRC clients.

The server accepts multiple TCP clients, handles IRC commands, manages users and channels, and sends protocol-style replies. It is designed around an event-driven model using non-blocking sockets.

This project helped me understand how real-time network servers work internally, from socket creation to client registration, command parsing, and channel management.

---

## Features

| Feature             | Description                                                 |
| ------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------- |
| TCP Server          | Accepts client connections over IPv4 TCP sockets            |
| Multiple Clients    | Handles several connected users at the same time            |
| Non-blocking I/O    | Uses an event-driven approach to avoid blocking the server  |
| Authentication      | Clients must authenticate using the server password         |
| User Registration   | Supports nickname and username registration                 |
| Channels            | Users can create, join, leave, and interact inside channels |
| Private Messages    | Supports direct messages between users                      |
| Channel Operators   | Operators can manage channel behavior and users             |
| Error Handling      | Sends appropriate replies for invalid commands or states    |
| Clean Disconnection | Handles client quit and unexpected disconnection            |

---

## Implemented Commands

| Command   | Description                           |
| --------- | ------------------------------------- |
| `PASS`    | Authenticate with the server password |
| `NICK`    | Set or change client nickname         |
| `USER`    | Register username information         |
| `JOIN`    | Join or create a channel              |
| `PART`    | Leave a channel                       |
| `PRIVMSG` | Send private or channel messages      |
| `KICK`    | Remove a user from a channel          |
| `INVITE`  | Invite a user to a channel            |
| `TOPIC`   | View or change a channel topic        |
| `MODE`    | Change channel modes                  |
| `PING`    | Keep the connection alive             |
| `QUIT`    | Disconnect from the server            |

Some commands are implemented according to the 42 project requirements and may not fully cover the complete IRC RFC specification.

---

## Build

Clone the repository:

```bash
git clone https://github.com/Mohahamdali/ft_irc.git
cd ft_irc
```

Compile the project:

```bash
make
```

Clean object files:

```bash
make clean
```

Remove object files and executable:

```bash
make fclean
```

Rebuild:

```bash
make re
```

---

## Usage

Run the server with a port and password:

```bash
./ircserv <port> <password>
```

Example:

```bash
./ircserv 6667 mypassword
```

---

## Testing With an IRC Client

You can connect using an IRC client such as `irssi`:

```bash
irssi
/connect localhost 6667 mypassword
```

You can also test manually with `nc`:

```bash
nc localhost 6667
```

Manual registration example:

```text
PASS mypassword
NICK alice
USER alice 0 * :Alice
JOIN #general
PRIVMSG #general :Hello from ft_irc
```

Second client example:

```text
PASS mypassword
NICK bob
USER bob 0 * :Bob
JOIN #general
PRIVMSG #general :Hello Alice
```

